;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:722,&quot;width&quot;:877,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:698,&quot;bytes&quot;:59686,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F94d4040d-1696-4727-8bea-3b2654fc4301_877x722.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F94d4040d-1696-4727-8bea-3b2654fc4301_877x722.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F94d4040d-1696-4727-8bea-3b2654fc4301_877x722.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F94d4040d-1696-4727-8bea-3b2654fc4301_877x722.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture></div></a> <polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line><figcaption class="image-caption"> <a href="https://unsplash.com/@justinlim?utm_content=creditCopyText&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_source=unsplash">贾斯汀·林</a>（Justin Lim）的<a href="https://unsplash.com/photos/man-holding-solar-panel-on-roof-Fpcy-AdFhUg?utm_content=creditCopyText&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_source=unsplash">照片</a></figcaption></figure></div><p>干扰富裕国家的市场需要理由。如果市场受到适当的监管，则是一种最大化国家总收入的非常有效的方法。不平等和贫穷的问题可以通过重新分配和提高工人谈判能力的措施来解决；偶尔的衰退可以通过货币和财政刺激来解决。这个基本的公式 - 称其为新自由主义/社会民主的混合经济 - 产生了地球上 <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_Development_Index#/media/File:HDI2022Incrimental.svg">最发达</a>和<a href="https://www.visualcapitalist.com/a-map-of-global-happiness-by-country-in-2024/">最快乐的</a>社会。如果您要通过让政府进来并开始使用一个国家的工业结构来弄乱该公式，那么您需要一个充分的理由。</p><p>美国和我们的民主盟友有一个<em>很好</em>的理由：<a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/in-which-british-writers-scold-america">国家安全</a>。中国轴心要求民主国家重建和增强自己的制造业，这需要以某种方式干扰自由市场。工业政策是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/economy/the-u-s-finally-has-a-strategy-to-compete-with-china-will-it-work-ce4ea6cf">其中的重要组成部分</a>。</p><p>但是，这些国家安全问题在过去五年中才真正普遍存在。在此<em>之前</em>，美国经济思维的转变实际上正在进行中。我记得在2017年参加彭博社会议，几乎每个人（大多数是来自科技，智囊团和媒体的一群进步的知识分子）都在谈论需要将工业政策带回​​。但是中国从未提及过 - 每个人引用的大理由是<em>气候变化</em>。</p><p>我记得我听说每个人都在谈论与气候变化的斗争如何需要在第二次世界大战的秩序上进行工业动员 - 建立绿色能源，改用电动汽车，改造我们的工业流程，改造或重建建筑物。而且市场行驶不够快。像1970年代吉米·卡特（Jimmy Carter）一样，我在2010年的朋友们认为，能源过渡可能<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moral_Equivalent_of_War_speech">与战争相当</a>。</p><p>这个想法一直进入拜登政府。在拜登的三项签名工业政策法案中，其中两项 - 《降低通货膨胀法》和《基础设施法案》主要旨在促进绿色能源行业以打击气候变化。 2010年代的进步知识分子取得了胜利。</p><p>但是现在，随着拜登对中国电动汽车，电池和太阳能电池板的新关税，该剧本有些翻转。许多进步的思想家为绿色工业政策的兴起而欢呼，这使美国将使绿色技术产品更昂贵。例如， <a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2024-05-28/biden-s-tariffs-on-china-evs-delay-clean-energy-worsen-climate-change?utm_source=website&amp;utm_medium=share&amp;utm_campaign=twitter">大卫·弗林格（David Fickling）写道</a>：</p><blockquote><p>政府已承诺要加速向电动汽车过渡。然而，为了减少进口的激增，它最近<a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-05-14/biden-imposes-sweeping-tariffs-on-chinese-chips-minerals-evs">宣布</a>对中国造成的电动汽车的100％关税，从而推迟了过渡，正确地坚持认为这是必不可少的。</p><p>拜登和他的官员似乎很困惑。他们可以使应对气候变化的重中之重，或者让他们的超越目标是保护美国制作人免受外国竞争的影响。他们不能同时做……</p><p>最后，这并不是那么复杂：如果气候变化是一种生存风险，那么良好，廉价中国电动汽车的产出激增是一件好事。</p></blockquote><p>迪伦·马修斯（Dylan Matthews）在三月份也<a href="https://www.vox.com/climate/2024/3/4/24087919/biden-tariff-chinese-ev-byd-battery-detroit">提出了类似的论点</a>：</p><blockquote><p> [中国电动汽车]绝对是尖叫的交易 - 正是那种可以使我们从天然气转向<a href="https://www.vox.com/electric-vehicles">电动汽车</a>过渡的产品……是美国人的问题吗？<a href="https://www.vox.com/joe-biden">拜顿政府</a>对阻止您购买BYD的产品的地狱般屈服，如果<a href="https://www.vox.com/donald-trump">唐纳德·特朗普</a>返回办公室，他也可能会与之抗争。</p><p>那是因为比顿汽车是在中国制造的，拜登和特朗普都致力于制定一项旨在避免比德产品的超国家主义贸易政策……中国电动汽车案是一个很好的证明，尽管如此，拜登政府可能会出于气候关注而激发的动机，渴望帮助美国汽车制造商，在今年11月赢得密歇根州的选举票，并升级对中国的冷战……如果它坚持下去的气候政策，它令人震惊地愿意，这是<em>更加</em>动力的。正在进行中。</p></blockquote><p> <a href="https://thehill.com/policy/energy-environment/4670967-joe-biden-china-tariffs-risk-downgrading-energy-transition/">其他人</a>已经<a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2024/05/16/china-tariffs-climate-evs-energy/">回应了</a>这一论点。</p><p>如果气候变化确实是美国经济政策发生重大变化的主要原因，那么弥补和马修斯将是正确的，而美国也应该遵循他们的建议。但是，尽管我的许多朋友和同事在2017年想到了什么，但气候变化实际上<em>并不是</em>产生工业政策的主要原因，也不会前进。因此，他们大喊大叫。</p><p>这样做的原因不仅是国家安全问题在美国精英的思想中优先考虑，尽管这肯定是事实。由于许多其他原因，气候变化不适合成为美国经济政策变化的主要驱动力。在公众舆论方面，它并没有激励投票公众，并且两党制的可能性较低。同时，廉价的中国进口商品可能不会成为绿色能源过渡的关键因素。</p><p>因此，尽管气候政策很重要，但它不能独自一人。取而代之的是，它一定只是一套旨在重新激发美国工业可能性的政策的一部分。</p><h4>气候变化是真实而重要的，但并没有激发选民</h4><p>任何否认人为气候变化的现实和重要性的人都将手指<a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/a-bunch-of-handy-charts-about-climate">牢牢地扎在耳边</a>。温度<a href="https://www.economist.com/graphic-detail/2024/01/12/eight-charts-illustrate-2023s-extreme-weather">稳步上升</a>，年复一年是有记录以来最热门的： </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F131bc157-fc0b-4cc8-a690-923a225a5594_1638x737.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F131bc157-fc0b-4cc8-a690-923a225a5594_1638x737.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F131bc157-fc0b-4cc8-a690-923a225a5594_1638x737.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F131bc157-fc0b-4cc8-a690-923a225a5594_1638x737.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F131bc157-fc0b-4cc8-a690-923a225a5594_1638x737.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F131bc157-fc0b-4cc8-a690-923a225a5594_1638x737.jpeg" width="1456" height="655" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/131bc157-fc0b-4cc8-a690-923a225a5594_1638x737.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:655,&quot;width&quot;:1456,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:325279,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F131bc157-fc0b-4cc8-a690-923a225a5594_1638x737.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F131bc157-fc0b-4cc8-a690-923a225a5594_1638x737.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F131bc157-fc0b-4cc8-a690-923a225a5594_1638x737.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F131bc157-fc0b-4cc8-a690-923a225a5594_1638x737.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption">资料来源： <a href="https://x.com/hausfath/status/1763992079477379514/">Zeke Hausfather</a></figcaption></figure></div><p>对于美国，加拿大和澳大利亚等富裕国家，气候变化的危害在<a href="https://nintil.com/wildfires-california/">野火风险增加</a>和<a href="https://www.bbc.com/future/article/20240311-why-climate-change-is-making-the-us-uninsurable">沿海洪水风险增加的</a>角度表现出来。对于像印度这样贫穷的赤道国家，它表现为<a href="https://www.reuters.com/world/india/indias-capital-sees-first-heat-related-death-this-year-media-reports-2024-05-30/">无法忍受的热浪</a>，导致水供应不足并使<a href="https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/c166xxd4y36o">城市条件不可分割</a>。更糟糕的是 -<a href="https://x.com/hausfath/status/1755681397229113836">模型预测</a>和<a href="https://x.com/hausfath/status/1788588264179593496">共识预测</a>都可以使气候在本世纪的2.7°C升高约2.7°C（很多），而即使是强大的全球努力，现在仍然涉及到现在的情况变得更糟。因此，请抓住您的帽子 - 这将是<a href="https://www.economist.com/films/2021/10/30/this-is-what-3degc-of-global-warming-looks-like">一个颠簸的旅程</a>。</p><p>因此，每个人都<em>应该</em>非常关心气候变化。但是我说那不会这么做。不幸的事实是，尽管数十年来的行动主义和精英言论，投票的公众并没有对气候问题高度重视。 Matt Yglesias在一月份解释了这一点： </p><div class="embedded-post-wrap" data-attrs="{&quot;id&quot;:140589619,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.slowboring.com/p/climate-is-the-problem&quot;,&quot;publication_id&quot;:159185,&quot;publication_name&quot;:&quot;Slow Boring &quot;,&quot;publication_logo_url&quot;:&quot;https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fceeb681e-a14d-4bbb-a8fe-951c29603e3f_256x256.png&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Climate is the problem&quot;,&quot;truncated_body_text&quot;:&quot;Center-left intellectuals like me have two passions in life: complaining about the things that we, personally, find annoying about far-left ideologues and wringing our hands about the electoral fortunes of the Democratic Party. Sometimes these two things coincide. We tend to live in urban areas, so we worried on a personal level about the spike in crime in 2020-2021 and (correctly) warned of the political risks of embracing soft-on-crime policies. But we are fallible and at times fall prey to the very human tendency to project our picayune concerns onto persuadable voters, while ignoring voter concerns that don&#8217;t line up with our own. And while insofar as &#8220;woke&#8221; politics leads to rising murders, that&#8217;s a very real political problem. And my sense is that a lot of people in my broad political space over-index on the idea that&quot;,&quot;date&quot;:&quot;2024-01-16T11:00:42.376Z&quot;,&quot;like_count&quot;:332,&quot;comment_count&quot;:580,&quot;bylines&quot;:[{&quot;id&quot;:580004,&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Matthew Yglesias&quot;,&quot;handle&quot;:&quot;matthewyglesias&quot;,&quot;previous_name&quot;:null,&quot;photo_url&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/20964455-401a-494d-a8ef-9835b34e9809_3024x3024.png&quot;,&quot;bio&quot;:&quot;Blogger, journalist, podcaster, trying to get back to my roots. &quot;,&quot;profile_set_up_at&quot;:&quot;2021-04-21T11:11:05.347Z&quot;,&quot;publicationUsers&quot;:[{&quot;id&quot;:18017,&quot;user_id&quot;:580004,&quot;publication_id&quot;:159185,&quot;role&quot;:&quot;admin&quot;,&quot;public&quot;:true,&quot;is_primary&quot;:false,&quot;publication&quot;:{&quot;id&quot;:159185,&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Slow Boring &quot;,&quot;subdomain&quot;:&quot;matthewyglesias&quot;,&quot;custom_domain&quot;:&quot;www.slowboring.com&quot;,&quot;custom_domain_optional&quot;:false,&quot;hero_text&quot;:&quot;Start your day with pragmatic takes on politics and public policy.&quot;,&quot;logo_url&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/ceeb681e-a14d-4bbb-a8fe-951c29603e3f_256x256.png&quot;,&quot;author_id&quot;:580004,&quot;theme_var_background_pop&quot;:&quot;#121BFA&quot;,&quot;created_at&quot;:&quot;2020-11-05T16:20:32.177Z&quot;,&quot;rss_website_url&quot;:null,&quot;email_from_name&quot;:&quot;Matthew Yglesias&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;Matthew Yglesias&quot;,&quot;founding_plan_name&quot;:&quot;Charismatic Authority&quot;,&quot;community_enabled&quot;:true,&quot;invite_only&quot;:false,&quot;payments_state&quot;:&quot;enabled&quot;,&quot;language&quot;:null,&quot;explicit&quot;:false}}],&quot;twitter_screen_name&quot;:&quot;mattyglesias&quot;,&quot;is_guest&quot;:false,&quot;bestseller_tier&quot;:10000}],&quot;utm_campaign&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;newsletter&quot;,&quot;language&quot;:&quot;en&quot;}" data-component-name="EmbeddedPostToDOM"><a class="embedded-post" native="true" href="https://www.slowboring.com/p/climate-is-the-problem?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_campaign=post_embed&amp;utm_medium=web"><div class="embedded-post-header"><img class="embedded-post-publication-logo" src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_56,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fceeb681e-a14d-4bbb-a8fe-951c29603e3f_256x256.png" loading="lazy"><span class="embedded-post-publication-name">缓慢的无聊</span></div><div class="embedded-post-title-wrapper"><div class="embedded-post-title">气候是问题</div></div><div class="embedded-post-body">像我这样的中心左翼知识分子在生活中有两种激情：抱怨我们个人对左翼意识形态感到烦人的事情，并为民主党的选举命运而挣扎。有时这两件事是重合的。我们倾向于生活在城市地区，因此我们担心个人对2020  -  2021年犯罪激增的层次，并（正确）警告采用柔软的犯罪政策的政治风险。但是我们很容易犯错，有时是人类倾向于将我们的Picayune担忧投射到可说服的选民的趋势，同时忽略了与我们自己不符的选民担忧。虽然“觉醒”的政治会导致谋杀案上升，但这是一个非常现实的政治问题。我的感觉是，我广阔的政治空间中的很多人都对……</div><div class="embedded-post-cta-wrapper"><span class="embedded-post-cta">阅读更多</span></div><div class="embedded-post-meta">5个月前·332个喜欢·580评论·Matthew Yglesias</div></div><p>一些摘录：</p><blockquote><p> [i]如果您略微调查了公众舆论，很明显，公众对气候行动的支持是一英里宽，一英寸深。例如，IPSOS发现， <a href="https://www.ipsos.com/sites/default/files/ct/news/documents/2023-04/Ipsos%20Global%20Advisor%20-%20Earth%20Day%202023%20-%20Full%20Report%20-%20WEB.pdf">只有25％的美国人表示，他们愿意缴纳更高的税款</a>来解决气候变化。 2019年路透社的一项民意调查特别询问，受访者是否要支付100美元来打击气候变化，<a href="https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSKCN1TR17X/">只有三分之一说是</a>。您是否愿意为应对气候变化的电费支付$ 10/个月？ <a href="https://www.cato.org/blog/68-americans-wouldnt-pay-10-month-higher-electric-bills-combat-climate-change">大多数人拒绝</a>。</p></blockquote><p>如果说服了气候变化的重要性，也许这可能会发生变化。但是激进主义者多年来一直在最大的刺耳，尽管这似乎有助于提高精英的认识（这很好！），但它几乎没有使气候变化成为普通公众的流行原因。现在，气候活动家 - 至少那些还没有<a href="https://www.aljazeera.com/program/newsfeed/2023/11/13/man-grabs-mic-from-greta-thunberg-at-climate-rally">转向巴勒斯坦的</a>人 - 专注于<a href="https://x.com/ZombiePanther2/status/1796002740121833614">抨击民主党人</a>，从事<a href="https://news.artnet.com/art-world/here-is-every-artwork-attacked-by-climate-activists-this-year-from-the-mona-lisa-to-girl-with-a-pearl-earring-2200804">不受欢迎的特技表演</a>，并<a href="https://x.com/RogerHallamCS21/status/1795734145223545338">提出</a>诸如“亚利桑那州凤凰城人口的12％，亚利桑那州人口的12％将死于2030年代的极端热量。”</p><p>它只是不起作用。选民<em>应该</em>关心，但他们坚定地拒绝照顾。数十年来，民主党人一直强调其言论的气候变化，美国人仍然没有准备好向化石燃料宣战。</p><p>同时，尽管共和党的很大一部分需要站在中国，但气候问题倾向于激活其党派本能。尽管一些共和党人确实支持基础设施法案和其他一些次要法案来促进电动汽车，但<em>零</em>投票赞成较大的减少通货膨胀法案。民意测验表明，电动汽车已成为文化战争的重点 - 自由主义者强烈赞同电动汽车，而保守派<a href="https://www.wsj.com/business/autos/another-roadblock-to-the-ev-transition-personal-politics-ab4e311b">则以2比1的利润不赞成他们</a>。</p><p>一个国家的经济政策的转变要求双方都必须加入 - 通常不是通过两党合作，而是通过竞争自己的邮票上的基本范式。艾森豪威尔（Eisenhower）和尼克松（Nixon）都在新交易上留下了烙印，而<a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/repost-much-of-what-youve-heard-about">卡特（Carter</a> ）和克林顿（Clinton）实施了“新自由主义”革命的关键部分。大多数民主党人和大多数共和党人肯定会在国家安全方面加入，并且都了解工业政策在该领域的重要性。但是，共和党只是拒绝气候政策作为对美国经济的指导方向。</p><p>因此气候变化将保持分裂。这不会使气候政策变得不可能，但它将阻止其成为经济决策的核心，重大的当务之急。</p><p>幸运的是，它不需要。</p><h4>即使气候并不总是优先＃1，绿色能源过渡也会发生</h4><p>减少美国排放的收益是适度的，但远非微不足道。<a href="https://x.com/sam_d_1995/status/1796161948632895858">一些分析发现</a>，与特朗普的政策相比，到2030年，拜登的经济政策将导致约17亿吨的二氧化碳等效排放量减少约17亿吨。这大约是<a href="https://ourworldindata.org/co2-emissions">2022年全球排放的4.6％</a> - 并不是很大，但也不是一无所有。在打击气候变化的斗争中，中国仍然比美国更重要（如今<a href="https://x.com/AssaadRazzouk/status/1795610609847013886">有希望它做得更好的迹象</a>），但美国当然可以做很多帮助。</p><p>这是美国温室气体排放来自的地方： </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7304bfc6-e980-47a7-ad47-0edf0727c123_393x389.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7304bfc6-e980-47a7-ad47-0edf0727c123_393x389.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7304bfc6-e980-47a7-ad47-0edf0727c123_393x389.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7304bfc6-e980-47a7-ad47-0edf0727c123_393x389.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7304bfc6-e980-47a7-ad47-0edf0727c123_393x389.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7304bfc6-e980-47a7-ad47-0edf0727c123_393x389.jpeg" width="393" height="389" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/7304bfc6-e980-47a7-ad47-0edf0727c123_393x389.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:389,&quot;width&quot;:393,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:29337,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7304bfc6-e980-47a7-ad47-0edf0727c123_393x389.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7304bfc6-e980-47a7-ad47-0edf0727c123_393x389.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7304bfc6-e980-47a7-ad47-0edf0727c123_393x389.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7304bfc6-e980-47a7-ad47-0edf0727c123_393x389.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption">资料来源：<a href="https://www.epa.gov/ghgemissions/sources-greenhouse-gas-emissions">美国环保局</a></figcaption></figure></div><p>为了脱碳，我们需要做以下四件事：</p><ol><li><p>切换到绿色能源 - 主要是由电池存储支持的太阳能，但也有一些核和风</p></li><li><p>切换到电动汽车，公共汽车和其他车辆</p></li><li><p>电气化家庭加热（和烹饪）</p></li><li><p>电气化一堆工业过程，例如钢和水泥，或使用其他绿色等效物</p></li></ol><p>基本上，您可以将其煮沸至1）通电，以及2）确保电网本身以绿色能量消失。</p><p>幸运的是，已经出现了两种奇迹技术，使这两项任务都比回到2010年或1990年<em>更</em>容易。呈指数下降。结果，太阳能在历史上的任何能源技术中都处于更快的扩展路径上： </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F35b2f9ec-3a0c-4343-801e-5bcbb61722de_937x528.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F35b2f9ec-3a0c-4343-801e-5bcbb61722de_937x528.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F35b2f9ec-3a0c-4343-801e-5bcbb61722de_937x528.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F35b2f9ec-3a0c-4343-801e-5bcbb61722de_937x528.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F35b2f9ec-3a0c-4343-801e-5bcbb61722de_937x528.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F35b2f9ec-3a0c-4343-801e-5bcbb61722de_937x528.jpeg" width="937" height="528" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/35b2f9ec-3a0c-4343-801e-5bcbb61722de_937x528.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:528,&quot;width&quot;:937,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:56787,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F35b2f9ec-3a0c-4343-801e-5bcbb61722de_937x528.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F35b2f9ec-3a0c-4343-801e-5bcbb61722de_937x528.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F35b2f9ec-3a0c-4343-801e-5bcbb61722de_937x528.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F35b2f9ec-3a0c-4343-801e-5bcbb61722de_937x528.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption">资料来源：<a href="https://www.nathanielbullard.com/presentations">纳特·布拉德（Nat Bullard）</a></figcaption></figure></div><p> <a href="https://ember-climate.org/insights/research/global-electricity-review-2024/">Ember最近的一份报告</a>发现，太阳能和风现在产生了全球电力的12％，这是实际的一代，而不是“容量”。当您将其添加到现有水力发电上时，可再生能源现在会产生大约30％的世界电力，并快速上升： </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6a3606fd-46c7-44be-a595-82c39b0c816c_1232x763.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6a3606fd-46c7-44be-a595-82c39b0c816c_1232x763.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6a3606fd-46c7-44be-a595-82c39b0c816c_1232x763.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6a3606fd-46c7-44be-a595-82c39b0c816c_1232x763.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6a3606fd-46c7-44be-a595-82c39b0c816c_1232x763.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6a3606fd-46c7-44be-a595-82c39b0c816c_1232x763.jpeg" width="1232" height="763" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/6a3606fd-46c7-44be-a595-82c39b0c816c_1232x763.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:763,&quot;width&quot;:1232,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:91097,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6a3606fd-46c7-44be-a595-82c39b0c816c_1232x763.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6a3606fd-46c7-44be-a595-82c39b0c816c_1232x763.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6a3606fd-46c7-44be-a595-82c39b0c816c_1232x763.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6a3606fd-46c7-44be-a595-82c39b0c816c_1232x763.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption">资料来源： <a href="https://ember-climate.org/insights/research/global-electricity-review-2024/">Ember</a></figcaption></figure></div><p>美国<a href="https://x.com/johnrhanger/status/1795765542004871293">没有落后</a>。<a href="https://www.eia.gov/electricity/monthly/epm_table_grapher.php?t=table_1_01">根据EIA的说法</a>，3月，太阳能和风能产生21.2％的美国电力，可再生能源产生29.9％，可再生能源和核核能产生了49.4％。</p><p>尽管拜登的气候政策很棒，但他们还没有太多的机会生效，而且许多国家没有类似的政策。迅速向可再生能源的转变是由使可再生能源（尤其是<a href="https://x.com/johnrhanger/status/1773314691185463622">太阳能和电池</a>）的技术改进驱动的。</p><p>我们可以通过观察国家和国家的行动来了解这一点，这些国家和国家对经济增长的关注比对气候变化更加关心经济增长。</p><p>印度尽管遭受了激烈的热浪，但仍将其重大优先级增长，并<a href="https://www.spglobal.com/commodityinsights/en/market-insights/latest-news/energy-transition/112923-cop28-india-doubles-down-on-right-to-increase-climate-emissions">保留继续使用化石燃料以西方国家在当时使用化石燃料工业化的理由继续使用化石燃料的权利</a>。然而，在今年的第一季度，自去年以来，在印度的太阳能装置<a href="https://x.com/sarthakgh/status/1794351907659829758">增加</a>了<em><a href="https://x.com/sarthakgh/status/1794351907659829758">六倍以上</a></em>。</p><p>得克萨斯州是一个非常保守的国家，也是美国化石燃料行业的中心，在建造太阳能方面，加利福尼亚和其他所有人都超过了： </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Faea67207-a32b-4c83-be9a-3be470028a57_1300x902.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Faea67207-a32b-4c83-be9a-3be470028a57_1300x902.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Faea67207-a32b-4c83-be9a-3be470028a57_1300x902.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Faea67207-a32b-4c83-be9a-3be470028a57_1300x902.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Faea67207-a32b-4c83-be9a-3be470028a57_1300x902.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Faea67207-a32b-4c83-be9a-3be470028a57_1300x902.jpeg" width="704" height="488.4676923076923" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/aea67207-a32b-4c83-be9a-3be470028a57_1300x902.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:902,&quot;width&quot;:1300,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:704,&quot;bytes&quot;:112257,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Faea67207-a32b-4c83-be9a-3be470028a57_1300x902.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Faea67207-a32b-4c83-be9a-3be470028a57_1300x902.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Faea67207-a32b-4c83-be9a-3be470028a57_1300x902.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Faea67207-a32b-4c83-be9a-3be470028a57_1300x902.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption">资料来源：<a href="https://x.com/curious_founder/status/1795831821529145426">迈克尔·托马斯</a></figcaption></figure></div><p>实际上，太阳能和风被证明是德克萨斯州<a href="https://x.com/douglewinenergy/status/1785429102352040197">最可靠的电力来源</a>。</p><p>同时，得克萨斯州和加利福尼亚州正在增加大量的电池存储，这使<a href="https://x.com/drvolts/status/1793743067645972773">日常太阳能的间歇性平滑</a>（即，您可以在夜间或下雨时存储能量）。这仍然留下了<em>季节性的</em>间歇性处理（冬天的太阳较弱），但这是一个容易解决的问题。至少，你可以过度建造更多的太阳能。</p><p>换句话说，带有电池存储的太阳能证明，现在它只是建造的最便宜的能量形式 - 只要您可以获得土地，通过许可过程，并将其连接到网格。而且，这一切都在中国太阳能电池板的25％的关税中发生。</p><p>现在，您可能会担心拜登（Biden）将中国太阳能电池板的关税<a href="https://www.bbc.com/news/business-69004520">从25％提高到50％，</a>这会终止太阳能繁荣。但它不会。首先，太阳能电池板变得如此便宜，以至于面板本身的成本<a href="https://www.energysage.com/local-data/solar-panel-cost/">仅占太阳系成本的一小部分</a>- 大部分是土地成本，安装劳动力等。因此，新的关税将提高太阳能的价格最多只有几个百分点 - 不足以影响太阳能与煤炭或天然气的成本计算。其次，美国太阳能制造能力本身<a href="https://www.utilitydive.com/news/solar-installation-capacity-manufacturing-modules/709414/">足以满足该国的一半</a>需求，甚至没有考虑到墨西哥或加拿大等地的进口。</p><p>鉴于中国对电池市场的占主导地位，电池从7.5％到25％的关税可能是一个更重要的因素，而且电池存储对于太阳能电力非常重要。但是，<a href="https://cleantechnica.com/2024/03/18/ev-battery-prices-dropping-a-lot-this-year-next/">预计电池成本将在未来两年内下降40％</a> ，而不仅仅是取消关税。同时，美国电池容量正在迅速提高，并且<a href="https://www.edf.org/sites/default/files/2023-12/EDF%20Analysis%20on%20US%20Battery%20Capacity%2012.13.23%20final%20v3.pdf">可以满足所有对电动汽车的需求</a>，因此，即使我们不考虑从墨西哥这样的国家进口，增加了满足电网存储需求的能力，即使和加拿大。电动汽车电池<a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-022-35393-0">也可以充当电网存储</a>。美国有<a href="https://www.newser.com/story/351027/massive-lithium-find-made-in-pennsylvania.html">很多锂</a>可以制作电池。</p><p>换句话说，现在太阳能和电池的技术革命正在进行中，无论关税如何，都会引入绿色电力时代。为了进一步加速过渡，现在最需要的是<em>监管</em>变化 -<a href="https://ifp.org/a-grand-bargain-for-permitting-reform/">允许改革</a>，消除土地使用限制以及改革过时且效率低下的<a href="https://www.volts.wtf/p/whats-the-deal-with-interconnection">互连队列系统</a>，以将电网连接到电网。</p><p>美国的另一个大转变是转向电动汽车。运输代表了美国排放量最大的单一类别，因此这非常重要。在这里，关税可能会产生更大的影响。 Biden&#39;s 100% tariffs on Chinese-made EVs are high enough that they effectively constitute a total ban. And China is the country that makes the world&#39;s cheapest EVs — and probably the highest-quality EVs too, at this point. So it&#39;s reasonable for David Fickling and Dylan Matthews to be concerned.</p><p> But so far, even without any significant amount of EV imports from China, the transition to EVs in the US <a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-05-28/the-slowdown-in-us-electric-vehicle-sales-looks-more-like-a-blip?sref=R8NfLgwS">has been going fine</a> :</p><blockquote><p> For every sign of an EV slowdown, another suggests an adolescent industry on the verge of its next growth spurt. In fact, for most automakers, even the first quarter was a blockbuster. Six of the 10 biggest EV makers in the US saw sales grow at a scorching pace compared to a year ago — up anywhere from 56% at Hyundai-Kia to 86% at Ford. A sampling of April sales similarly <a href="https://insideevs.com/news/720163/kia-global-ev-sales-april2024/">came in hot</a> .</p></blockquote><p> The slowdown this year in US EV sales has nothing to do with China; it&#39;s all about Tesla suddenly failing to offer new products (including a promised cheaper EV). Tesla still makes most of the EVs that Americans buy, but the company has <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/why-china-is-defeating-tesla">been faltering lately</a> . That means there will be a lull in sales as other automakers — American companies, but also German and Korean companies — ramp up from a low base. But ramp up they will, and the EV boom will continues, especially as batter capacity expands and costs keep coming down.</p><p> And eventually, a tipping point will come where EVs just rapidly take over the entire auto fleet in the US Here&#39;s how I explained it in <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/the-traditional-auto-industry-is">a post last year</a> :</p><blockquote><p> There&#39;s a network effect between gas stations and cars on the road — the more gas stations there are, the more convenient it is to drive, and the more people drive, the more profitable it is to run a gas station. This is why we have a lot of cars and a lot of gas stations; they reinforce each other.</p><p> By taking internal combustion traffic off the road, EVs are going to make gas stations less profitable to run. Gas stations have fixed costs that they need to make up for by catering to large volumes of customers; when they can cater to fewer customers, their fixed costs are harder to pay, and some go out of business (or switch entirely to EV charging stations). When the number of gasoline-powered cars on the road goes down by double-digit percentages, it&#39;s going to lead to a lot of closures or conversions.</p><p> When some gas stations vanish, it makes it harder to drive an internal combustion car as your primary mode of transport.这是因为加油站较少且间距较远。 This creates range anxiety if you&#39;re on a long trip, but it also just forces you to drive farther and every time you fill up. That gives people an incentive to switch to an electric.</p></blockquote><p> Now, it&#39;s true that a flood of cheap Chinese imports would probably make this tipping point happen a bit sooner —Chinese EVs would be a bit cheaper than Teslas or Kias, and this would spur modestly faster adoption. But the emissions benefits of that modest acceleration would be more limited than people think. The reason is that the manufacturing processes for EVs are not yet decarbonized, and so EVs produced today have only <a href="https://www.visualcapitalist.com/life-cycle-emissions-evs-vs-combustion-engine-vehicles/#google_vignette">modest life-cycle emissions benefits</a> compared to ICE cars. That will change in a few years, of course, as the electrical grid decarbonizes and as EVs are used to make more EVs. But enticing a few Americans to switch to EVs a few years earlier than they otherwise would will have only limited benefits for the climate.</p><p> In other words, the green energy transition in the US is already happening, driven first and foremost by technological advancements, with Biden&#39;s industrial policy giving an extra push. The biggest bottlenecks in that push are regulatory barriers — NEPA and other permitting reform laws, the broken grid interconnection system, and so on — rather than a lack of sufficiently cheap Chinese imports.</p><h4> Climate policy as part of a bigger industrial strategy</h4><p> Meanwhile, some progressives are now making persuasive arguments that Biden&#39;s approach, tariffs and all, is the right long-term approach. <a href="https://heatmap.news/politics/biden-climate-policy">Robinson Meyer writes</a> that by keeping US manufacturers in the political coalition for climate action, protectionism will actually help sustain the political will for continued decarbonization, even in the face of Republican hostility:</p><blockquote><p> This is the guiding logic of Biden&#39;s climate policy: that American politics must have a powerful, durable, and flexible pro-decarbonization coalition if the US is to succeed in reaching net zero. Achieving this coalition is the underlying aim of the IRA, the EPA rules, and — yes — the recent tariffs. This is what I wish critics understood about the president&#39;s climate strategy: Biden&#39;s strategy won&#39;t have succeeded if the US makes some headway on emissions but imports all of its decarbonization tech from China. The US actually has to develop its own supply chain and manufacturing base to build the kind of deep economic coalition that can sustain long-term decarbonization. This is why trade restrictions have become so central to the administration&#39;s world view.</p></blockquote><p>这里的论点是，如果美国在几年内获得稍微便宜的中国进口产品，但这会让底特律破产，并摧毁拜登辛辛苦苦建立的新兴美国电池制造业，这将引起对气候政策的强烈抵制。 But if climate policy remains wedded to American factory jobs, revitalization of declining American regions, and the profits of American companies, then even GOP culture wars won&#39;t be able to kill it.</p><p> I don&#39;t know whether Meyer is right, but this seems very plausible. As noted above, the political coalition for climate policy by itself is very weak, and apathy about the issue is widespread. But if climate policy is wedded to industrialism — which, yes, includes protectionism — the number and diversity of stakeholders in climate policy goes up dramatically.</p><p> Zachary Carter, meanwhile, <a href="https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2024/05/biden-china-alexander-hamilton-tariffs-electric-cars-green-energy.html?utm_medium=social&amp;utm_campaign=traffic&amp;utm_source=article&amp;utm_content=twitter_share">argues that maintaining</a> US domestic industrial capacity is superior to relying entirely on the Chinese:</p><blockquote><p> Where the fight against climate change is concerned, more is more, and friends of both the planet and geopolitical stability should want the world&#39;s largest economy to be involved in the green technology of the future. To that end, Biden&#39;s tariffs are a necessary step…Tariffs can&#39;t do the work of economic development alone. They&#39;ll have to be harmonized with green tech subsidies from Biden&#39;s Inflation Reduction Act, coordinated with international allies, and adjusted in response to geopolitical change.</p></blockquote><p> I think this is a good argument, but it&#39;s a little vague as written, so let me try to flesh it out. If China massively subsidizes batteries, EVs, and solar panels, and if the US opens its markets to these products completely, it will incur long-term risks. For example, a war with China, or other geopolitical tensions, could abruptly cut off America&#39;s source of green tech products.想象一下，如果 70% 的美国人驾驶中国制造的电动汽车，而中国突然切断贸易，使美国人无法购买新车或获得替换零件，甚至使用内置后门将每个人的汽车变成砖头。 That would leave many Americans just as helpless and stranded as when the Saudis reduced oil supplies in 1973 or Iran cut off oil in 1979.</p><p> That risk, in turn, will make Americans wary about climate policy. If fighting climate change means making their livelihoods dependent on the whim of the Chinese government, they will be unlikely to embrace it. But if climate policy means building up US domestic industrial capacity, it will be more robust to shocks, and therefore less risky for Americans.</p><p> Carter&#39;s idea, in a nutshell, is that it&#39;s good for a country to have some degree of control over the technologies that are essential to its policy goals. That is a smart and reasonable argument.</p><p> In other words, the 2010s dream that climate change would be the moral equivalent of war — an overriding, unifying national challenge that would spur deep changes in America&#39;s economic system — is not going to come true. But something even better <em>is</em> probably going to come true. Climate policy is going to be one piece of an integrated suite of policies for reindustrializing America. National security will be the top priority, but thanks to progress in green energy technology, that imperative will also entail switching America to solar and batteries. And because climate policy will be wedded to a broad coalition of stakeholders, it&#39;ll be at least somewhat insured against cancellation by Republican antipathy and voter apathy.</p><p> Climate policy isn&#39;t going to drive the car, but it will be along for the ride. </p><div><hr></div><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/climate-is-just-one-piece-of-industrial?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"> <a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/climate-is-just-one-piece-of-industrial?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share"><span>分享</span></a></p><p></p><p></p>;
Happy fun Cold War 2 updateIt's getting a little warmer out there. https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/happy-fun-cold-war-2-update https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/happy-fun-cold-war-2-updateNoah Smith Wed, 29 May 2024 07:50:58 GMT <div class="captioned-image-container"><figure> <a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Feb609a1b-dcb6-4dfc-beb9-0150c08ab825_966x415.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Feb609a1b-dcb6-4dfc-beb9-0150c08ab825_966x415.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Feb609a1b-dcb6-4dfc-beb9-0150c08ab825_966x415.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Feb609a1b-dcb6-4dfc-beb9-0150c08ab825_966x415.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Feb609a1b-dcb6-4dfc-beb9-0150c08ab825_966x415.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Feb609a1b-dcb6-4dfc-beb9-0150c08ab825_966x415.jpeg" width="966" height="415" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/eb609a1b-dcb6-4dfc-beb9-0150c08ab825_966x415.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:415,&quot;width&quot;:966,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:127897,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Feb609a1b-dcb6-4dfc-beb9-0150c08ab825_966x415.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Feb609a1b-dcb6-4dfc-beb9-0150c08ab825_966x415.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Feb609a1b-dcb6-4dfc-beb9-0150c08ab825_966x415.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Feb609a1b-dcb6-4dfc-beb9-0150c08ab825_966x415.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture></div></a> <polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></figure></div><p> OK fine, I lied. This Cold War 2 update is neither happy nor fun.但这是必要且重要的。</p><p> Half a year ago, when <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/a-lot-of-what-you-see-in-the-news">I wrote that</a> a lot of what we see in the news can be explained by the existence of a cold war between a China/Russia bloc and a democratic bloc, it was a controversial thesis. Now it&#39;s becoming conventional wisdom, and attention is shifting toward how to prevent Cold War 2 from becoming <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/americans-are-still-not-worried-enough">World War 3</a> .</p><p> Diplomat and international relations professor Philip Zelikow has <a href="https://tnsr.org/2024/05/confronting-another-axis-history-humility-and-wishful-thinking/">a truly excellent essay</a> about our present moment in geopolitics, which I encourage you to read. He argues that the Axis, the Soviet-China partnership at the beginning of Cold War 1, and the present quasi-alliance between China, Russia, Iran, and North Korea all have much in common. Their overriding goal is to topple the United States. This means that the US can&#39;t simply withdraw behind its oceans and adopt a posture of isolation or neutrality; the US itself, and its power and wealth, is the target.</p><p> Zelikow also argues that the mid-2020s are very similar not just to the 1930s (as everyone talks about), but also to the late 1940s and early 1950s. In those decades, a third world war <em>almost</em> broke out between the US and the USSR/China. The Korean War happened, China invaded Korea as part of that war, and the USSR almost invaded Yugoslavia. Only strong deterrence by the US, the caution of Stalin and Mao, and distrust between the USSR and China averted the danger. Now, Zelikow argues, we&#39;re in another critical period. It all depends on the choices of the leaders of the New Axis (my term, not his), and here he is not optimistic:</p><blockquote><p> I believe the anti-American partnership has probably decided to double down.他们可能正在认真准备一段时期的重大对抗。 My view on this rests on my analysis of the history presented above as well as some key assessments of Moscow, Tehran, Beijing, and — to a lesser extent — Pyongyang.</p><p> Xi and Putin regard themselves as world-historical men of destiny. They believe they are capable of decisive, strategic action. Xi ranks himself with Mao and Stalin. Putin evokes the memory of Peter the Great. In China, Russia, and Iran the information and decision environments are cloistered…In China, Russia, and Iran the propaganda ministries have already been preparing their populations for a time of war, great sacrifice, and existential struggle.</p></blockquote><p> And he warns that the US no longer has the industrial strength to win a direct confrontation, as it did in former conflicts:</p><blockquote><p> China is preparing for war. I am not saying it seeks a war. But, publicly and privately, the Chinese Communist Party is mobilizing its country for one…For the last 10 years, China has been working hard on preparing and refining its plans for national defense mobilization…One lesson to them from the Ukraine war is the shallow and fragile character of the US defense-industrial base. Chinese manufacturing capacity now exceeds both the United States and Europe put together…There is little net public support in the United States for further big increases in defense spending beyond current levels. Yet despite an uptick in spending after Russia&#39;s invasion of Ukraine, Michael Brown notes that “America has a smaller military with older and less equipment than at any time in memory.”</p></blockquote><p> He predicts that China will move on Taiwan with a blockade rather than an invasion, attempting to bring the island to its knees by simply asserting that it&#39;s a Chinese province and daring any outside powers to treat it otherwise. An invasion would be <a href="https://ig.ft.com/taiwan-battlegrounds/">extremely difficult and risky,</a> and would definitely <a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2024-01-09/if-china-invades-taiwan-it-would-cost-world-economy-10-trillion?sref=R8NfLgwS">generate huge losses for the world economy</a> , with China itself being hard-hit. A blockade, in contrast, would dare Taiwan and its protectors to make escalatory moves, while at least offering the possibility of a cheap, bloodless conquest.</p><p> In the past few weeks, a number of events have occurred that strongly support Zelikow&#39;s core arguments and predictions. In response to the election of a new Taiwanese president, China has surrounded Taiwan with warships, obviously conducting a dry run for an actual blockade of the type Zelikow describes. And Russia is making a number of aggressive moves toward NATO countries, signaling that he won&#39;t be satisfied with conquering Ukraine.</p><p> Let&#39;s go through some of those scary developments.</p><h4> The New Axis is making moves</h4><p> Taiwan recently had an election. Basically, in Taiwanese politics, you have two main parties — the KMT, which favors a more conciliatory approach toward China and closer engagement, and the DPP, which favors distancing Taiwan from China. The KMT won the legislature, while the DPP — thanks in part to a third-party spoiler candidate — won the presidency. (The outgoing president, Tsai Ing-wen, was also DPP, but she was termed out.)</p><p> In his inaugural speech, the new DPP president, Lai Ching-te, <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/article/2024/may/22/china-warns-of-reprisals-against-taiwan-after-presidents-inauguration-speech">urged China to leave Taiwan alone</a> and alluded to <a href="https://x.com/WenchiY/status/1795105287633784915">the island&#39;s autonomy</a> , while falling short of asserting Taiwan&#39;s formal independence — a pretty standard DPP position. But whereas in the past, China reacted with annoyance and protests to such speeches, this time it <a href="https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/cqvv29gpqn1o">surrounded Taiwan with warships</a> : </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F09c0b2ea-8093-4601-a495-085b6a613645_1014x1197.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F09c0b2ea-8093-4601-a495-085b6a613645_1014x1197.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F09c0b2ea-8093-4601-a495-085b6a613645_1014x1197.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F09c0b2ea-8093-4601-a495-085b6a613645_1014x1197.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F09c0b2ea-8093-4601-a495-085b6a613645_1014x1197.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F09c0b2ea-8093-4601-a495-085b6a613645_1014x1197.jpeg" width="614" height="724.810650887574" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/09c0b2ea-8093-4601-a495-085b6a613645_1014x1197.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:1197,&quot;width&quot;:1014,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:614,&quot;bytes&quot;:190840,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F09c0b2ea-8093-4601-a495-085b6a613645_1014x1197.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F09c0b2ea-8093-4601-a495-085b6a613645_1014x1197.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F09c0b2ea-8093-4601-a495-085b6a613645_1014x1197.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F09c0b2ea-8093-4601-a495-085b6a613645_1014x1197.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption">资料来源：<a href="https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/cqvv29gpqn1o">法新社</a></figcaption></figure></div><p>This is obviously a rehearsal for a real blockade — the exact thing that Zelikow predicts. Not only are they a rehearsal in the sense of being a training exercise, but repeated almost-blockades of this type might lull both Taiwan and the US into being surprised when the real version comes.</p><p> Meanwhile, China is making various other moves that look an awful lot like military preparations. It&#39;s preparing a <a href="https://x.com/IndoPac_Info/status/1794762314983592073">large armada of ferries</a> to support a possible amphibious assault. It&#39;s <a href="https://x.com/abcampbell/status/1792968340748620266">stockpiling</a> copper, iron, food, and energy. It&#39;s <a href="https://x.com/ianellisjones/status/1787277873516011804?t=JC0Cq8yGW9d68NW0I4ReYw&amp;s=19">buying up gold</a> and reducing its official holdings of US government bonds, an obvious hedge against financial sanctions.等等。</p><p> Also, consider Chinese government rhetoric. The government&#39;s main TV station is <a href="https://x.com/StephenMcDonell/status/1793937205049635167">beating the war drums</a> pretty hard: </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6dd2e8d0-59c9-4e70-b822-7dee31515a36_796x701.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6dd2e8d0-59c9-4e70-b822-7dee31515a36_796x701.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6dd2e8d0-59c9-4e70-b822-7dee31515a36_796x701.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6dd2e8d0-59c9-4e70-b822-7dee31515a36_796x701.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6dd2e8d0-59c9-4e70-b822-7dee31515a36_796x701.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6dd2e8d0-59c9-4e70-b822-7dee31515a36_796x701.jpeg" width="670" height="590.0376884422111" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/6dd2e8d0-59c9-4e70-b822-7dee31515a36_796x701.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:701,&quot;width&quot;:796,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:670,&quot;bytes&quot;:158898,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6dd2e8d0-59c9-4e70-b822-7dee31515a36_796x701.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6dd2e8d0-59c9-4e70-b822-7dee31515a36_796x701.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6dd2e8d0-59c9-4e70-b822-7dee31515a36_796x701.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6dd2e8d0-59c9-4e70-b822-7dee31515a36_796x701.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></figure></div><p> China is also issuing threats toward Japan, which is <a href="https://thediplomat.com/2024/05/yes-japan-will-defend-taiwan/">likely to get involved</a> in a Taiwan conflict due to its own strategic vulnerabilities. China&#39;s ambassador to Japan <a href="https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2024/05/22/japan/politics/japan-protest-china-envoy-taiwan-remark/">declared</a> that &quot;once the country of Japan is tied to the tanks plotting to split China, the Japanese people will be brought into the fire.”</p><p> US intelligence also believes that China is now <a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-05-02/us-spies-see-china-russia-militaries-working-closer-on-taiwan?sref=R8NfLgwS">working closely with the Russians</a> on a Taiwan invasion scenario:</p><blockquote><p> US intelligence officials assess that Russia and China are working more closely together on military issues, including a potential invasion of Taiwan, prompting new planning across the government to counter a potential scenario in which the countries fight in coordination.</p></blockquote><p> In other words, if US intelligence is correct, an attack on Taiwan is likely to trigger a more general attack on democratic countries by the China-Russia axis.</p><p> Russia appears to be preparing for a more general confrontation with NATO in Europe. It recently <a href="https://x.com/visegrad24/status/1793688281135386986?t=D--kC0fh8kFhhdRR875R6g&amp;s=19">removed the river buoys</a> demarcating its border with Estonia. Estonia is the NATO country that&#39;s probably first in line to get invaded if Russia goes to war with NATO, given its small size and population, its exposed geographic position, and its large population of Russian speakers whose existence could provide Russia with an excuse for an攻击。</p><p> Meanwhile, Russia is stepping up what appears to be a sabotage campaign against Europe. Poland&#39;s prime minister has declared that Russia was likely behind <a href="https://x.com/EHunterChristie/status/1793186620465680593?t=qDmKDgLALSmpQl-XBRq8qQ&amp;s=19">the burning of a shopping mall</a> in Warsaw, and <a href="https://x.com/JayinKyiv/status/1793275289264361612">many suspect</a> that it was also behind a fire at Novo Nordisk&#39;s headquarters in Copenhagen. This is in addition to various other <a href="https://x.com/PerErikSchulze/status/1794828268480438514">aggressive moves</a> . It&#39;s not clear what all this is supposed to accomplish — scaring Europe into disunity and inaction, perhaps? — but it certainly seems to indicate an aggressive Russian posture toward NATO.</p><p> The reason Putin can be so confident in this slow-building aggression is that he knows his superpower ally has his back. Putin recently <a href="https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/putin-xi-agree-deepen-partnership-russia-advances-ukraine-war-rcna152528">went to meet Xi in China</a> , and the two promised to strengthen their “no limits partnership”. Xi even <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R14CypJvD0s">gave Putin a hug</a> — a rare sign of personal affection from a Chinese leader.</p><p> And there&#39;s evidence that those words are being backed up with deeds. China is buying huge amounts of Russian oil, keeping the company&#39;s economy afloat. It&#39;s selling the Russians huge amounts of <a href="https://www.reuters.com/world/eu-sees-signs-china-supplying-dual-use-components-russia-dombrovskis-says-2024-04-18/">dual-use technology</a> to keep its military machine humming despite Western sanctions. And <a href="https://www.reuters.com/world/uk-defence-minister-says-china-working-supply-lethal-aid-russia-2024-05-22/">the UK now believes</a> that China is providing or preparing to provide Russia with lethal aid — actual weaponry — for the Ukraine war.</p><p> In other words, Zelikow appears to be absolutely right that the Xi-Putin partnership is a much more solid and active alliance than either the WW2 Axis or the Stalin-Mao cooperation in the early years of Cold War 1. Dreams of severing Russia from China by offering it Ukraine on a silver platter were always highly unrealistic, but now they&#39;re just utterly laughable. Nor will the threat of sanctions be sufficient to deter China from supporting its ally&#39;s war effort forever.</p><p> And Zelikow also appears to be absolutely right that this alliance has the <em>strategic initiative</em> — China and Russia are making all the moves, and the US and its allies are scrambling to respond. Yet respond we must.</p><h4> What the US and its allies can do right now</h4><p> Zelikow is not the first international relations scholar to identify the present moment as a crisis that will determine what type of conflict will unfold between the New Allies and the New Axis. In his book <em><a href="https://www.amazon.com/Danger-Zone-Coming-Conflict-China/dp/1324021306">Danger Zone</a></em> with Michael Beckley, my former colleague <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/interview-hal-brands-international">Hal Brands</a> argues that cold wars are characterized by early pivot points or crises that can easily mushroom into all-out war. Only by shoring up deterrence and defining boundary lines can a cold war go truly cold — it&#39;s a sprint of a few years, followed by a marathon of a few decades.</p><p>我写的关于《冷战2》的大部分内容都是关于美国需要做什么才能为这场长达数十年的马拉松做好准备。 Reviving US manufacturing, restoring state capacity, strengthening old alliances and building new ones, maintaining America&#39;s technological edge, and so on — these are all efforts that would take many years to accomplish. Fortunately, I see a lot of other people coming to similar conclusions. For example, Matt Yglesias has an excellent post about how long-term national security requires us to embrace high-volume skilled immigration and expand trade with allies and potential allies: </p><div class="embedded-post-wrap" data-attrs="{&quot;id&quot;:144723988,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.slowboring.com/p/the-economics-of-the-new-cold-war&quot;,&quot;publication_id&quot;:159185,&quot;publication_name&quot;:&quot;Slow Boring &quot;,&quot;publication_logo_url&quot;:&quot;https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%