quot;:&quot;https://bucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/bbe0ccd5-353e-44b7-a31f-3ec42ef5c3ae_479x372.png&quot;,&quot;bio&quot;:&quot;https://constructionphysics.substack.com/&quot;,&quot;profile_set_up_at&quot;:&quot;2021-05-18T15:38:47.109Z&quot;,&quot;publicationUsers&quot;:[{&quot;id&quot;:238797,&quot;user_id&quot;:3518108,&quot;publication_id&quot;:104058,&quot;role&quot;:&quot;admin&quot;,&quot;public&quot;:true,&quot;is_primary&quot;:false,&quot;publication&quot;:{&quot;id&quot;:104058,&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Construction Physics&quot;,&quot;subdomain&quot;:&quot;constructionphysics&quot;,&quot;custom_domain&quot;:&quot;www.construction-physics.com&quot;,&quot;custom_domain_optional&quot;:false,&quot;hero_text&quot;:&quot;Essays about buildings, infrastructure, and industrial technology.&quot;,&quot;logo_url&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/2c663799-8d26-4456-8c14-8283b618f705_590x590.png&quot;,&quot;author_id&quot;:3518108,&quot;theme_var_background_pop&quot;:&quot;#B599F1&quot;,&quot;created_at&quot;:&quot;2020-09-27T22:51:49.282Z&quot;,&quot;rss_website_url&quot;:null,&quot;email_from_name&quot;:&quot;Construction Physics&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;Brian Potter&quot;,&quot;founding_plan_name&quot;:&quot;Founding Member&quot;,&quot;community_enabled&quot;:true,&quot;invite_only&quot;:false,&quot;payments_state&quot;:&quot;enabled&quot;,&quot;language&quot;:null,&quot;explicit&quot;:false}}],&quot;is_guest&quot;:false,&quot;bestseller_tier&quot;:100}],&quot;utm_campaign&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;newsletter&quot;,&quot;language&quot;:&quot;en&quot;}" data-component-name="EmbeddedPostToDOM"><a class="embedded-post" native="true" href="https://www.construction-physics.com/p/how-to-build-300000-airplanes-in?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_campaign=post_embed&amp;utm_medium=web"><div class="embedded-post-header"><img class="embedded-post-publication-logo" src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_56,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2c663799-8d26-4456-8c14-8283b618f705_590x590.png" loading="lazy"><span class="embedded-post-publication-name">建筑物理</span></div><div class="embedded-post-title-wrapper"><div class="embedded-post-title">如何在五年内建造 30 万架飞机</div></div><div class="embedded-post-body">同盟国凭借美国巨大的工业产出赢得了第二次世界大战，这已不是什么秘密。甚至在美国参战之前，美国人就向盟军提供了价值数亿美元的装备，并且在 1938 年至 1943 年间，美国...</div><div class="embedded-post-cta-wrapper"><span class="embedded-post-cta">阅读更多</span></div><div class="embedded-post-meta">12 天前 · 148 个赞 · 36 条评论 · 布莱恩·波特</div></div><p>令人惊奇的是，美国几乎从零开始就将这个行业整合在一起：</p><blockquote><p> 1937年，美国生产了约3,100架飞机，其中大部分是小型私人飞机。战前，美国制造的飞机价值约为罐头生产价值的四分之一，而仅占汽车生产价值的 3.5%……</p><p>生产赢得战争所需的飞机需要对飞机工业进行彻底转型。 1939 年至 1944 年间……生产的飞机总重量……增加了 64 倍。1940 年，机身行业仅雇佣了 59,000 名员工；三年后，这一数字达到了 939,000 个，另外还有 339,000 个飞机发动机工厂……战争结束时，飞机发动机工厂的占地面积从 170 万平方英尺增加到 7500 万平方英尺，单个大型发动机工厂的占地面积比原来的还要大。被整个战前发动机工业所使用。</p></blockquote><p>美国是如何完成这一令人难以置信的工业壮举的？波特指出了几个关键因素。</p><p>首先是<strong>稳定的需求来源</strong>。这一需求来自英国和法国，它们在二战前夕和战争初期订购了战机以对抗纳粹。这种可预测的需求使美国制造商能够承担必要的巨大风险，将工厂规模扩大数倍。所涉及的现金还直接帮助美国飞机公司为此次扩张提供资金。</p><p>另一个因素是<strong>充足的融资</strong>，其中大部分来自国防工厂公司，该公司基本上是一家为国防生产提供资金的大型国有银行。提出 DPC 想法的人是通用汽车公司前高管比尔·克努森 (Bill Knudsen)。克努森的照片位于这篇文章的顶部，他是优秀历史书<em><a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/book-review-freedoms-forge">《自由的熔炉》</a></em>的主角。重要的是，克努森和他在罗斯福政府中的雇主有先见之明，知道一场重大战争即将到来，并在炸弹开始落下<em>之前</em>大规模扩大美国的制造业。</p><p>第三个因素是<strong>现有的工业能力</strong>。美国拥有大量生产汽车、电器等的工厂，其中许多工厂很快被重新用于飞机和飞机发动机的制造。美国还拥有许多“第一产业”——铝冶炼厂等——能够为飞机工业提供所需的所有原材料。</p><p>第四个因素是<strong>女性</strong>，她们满足了大型飞机工厂约 40% 的劳动力需求。 The famous Rosie the Riveter was based on these workers.</p><p>在文章的最后，波特揭示了他认为现代美国可以从令人惊叹的二战飞机生产工作中学到的教训：</p><blockquote><p>他的成功具有很大的偶然性。不幸的是，美国没有做好扩大其飞机工业的准备……政府和行业都没有适当的组织基础设施来应对规模扩大，也没有计划创建它……直到 1942 年，即德国入侵波兰和法国三年后作为回应，英国对德国宣战，美国的飞机产量确实增加了，甚至这也是因为英国和法国的大量早期订单以及像比尔·克努森这样有远见的人的工作才可能实现的，他们知道这需要多长时间扩大制造业务……</p><p>第二次世界大战的飞机生产表明，复杂的制造业有可能实现令人难以置信的快速增长。但它也显示了扩大规模的局限性。即使在紧急情况下，有些事情也只能加速这么多，而成功取决于事先做了哪些准备。</p></blockquote><p>这对于美国当前的局势显然非常重要。我们<a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/americans-are-still-not-worried-enough">甚至不太担心</a>与中国的冲突，因此我们没有做出任何类似于为扩大国防工业规模所需的投资或监管改革的事情。来自乌克兰和台湾的订单<em>可能</em>为美国国防工业的振兴提供稳定的需求，但我国政府一直未能提供必要的资金。</p><p>我担心，唯一吸取美国二战生产奇迹教训的国家是中国。</p><h4> 2. 美国两党是否达成了新的“新民粹主义”共识？</h4><p>大卫·莱昂哈特 (David Leonhardt) 在《纽约时报》上发表了<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2024/05/19/briefing/centrism-washington-neopopulism.html">一篇精彩的文章</a>，汇集了美国政府最近发生的两条重要线索：</p><ol><li><p>两党合作悄然增加（马特·伊格莱西亚斯称之为“<a href="https://www.slowboring.com/p/the-rise-and-importance-of-secret">秘密国会</a>”）</p></li><li><p>经济思想从新自由主义向工业主义的转变</p></li></ol><p>在我看来，莱昂哈特正确地指出了这一转变背后的两个因素：</p><ol><li><p>中国领导的威权集团的崛起，其实力可与美国相媲美或超过</p></li><li><p>几十年来新自由主义政策似乎未能帮助工人阶级</p></li></ol><p>以下是一些摘录：</p><blockquote><p>中间派这个概念本身就是许多进步派和保守派所厌恶的，它让人联想到一种软弱的温和派。但新的中间主义并不总是那么温和。强制出售流行的社交应用程序并不完全是胆怯的行为，与中国和俄罗斯对抗也不是胆怯的行为。重建美国基础设施和加强国内半导体产业的法案是雄心勃勃的经济政策……</p><p>新中心主义……是对新自由主义未能实现的认识……取而代之的是一种新的世界观。称之为新民粹主义……</p><p>未来可能还会有哪些新民粹主义政策？制定更多应对中国崛起的立法和制定更多产业政策是可能的。确保美国能够获得锂和铜等关键矿产的法案将符合……帮助年轻家庭的政策也是合理的……</p><p>几十年来，华盛顿推行了一系列许多选民不喜欢的政策，而且这些政策<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/10/24/briefing/the-american-dream.html">并没有</a>达到其承诺的结果。许多公民感到沮丧是可以理解的。 That frustration has led to the stirrings of a neopopulism that seeks to reinvigorate the American economy and compete with the country&#39;s global rivals.尽管这个国家两极分化，但它的两个政党至少在努力回应这一现实，而且他们发现了意想不到的共同点。</p></blockquote><p>我认为这是一篇非常有洞察力且及时的帖子。我认为“新民粹主义”一词不会持续存在，主要是因为“民粹主义”一词的负面含义。但我也认为“民粹主义”并不是描述这里正在发生的事情的正确框架。美国人总体上<a href="https://www.pewresearch.org/global/2024/05/01/americans-remain-critical-of-china/">对中国持负面看法</a>，但为真正威慑和制衡中国而采取的许多实际政策措施——如出口管制、半导体补贴、扩大联盟等等——实际上是精英项目，而不是试图取悦中国选民。</p><p>与此同时，一些最重要的两党努力——比如<a href="https://www.democracydocket.com/news-alerts/biden-signs-electoral-count-reform-act-into-law/">计票改革</a>——却悄然进行，因为如果引起公众的关注，就会激活两党基础的党派能量，做出合理的妥协。更难。伊格莱西亚斯称其为“秘密国会”是有原因的——该国大部分地区仍然处于痛苦、暴躁的情绪中，民粹主义能量总体上仍然推动国会走向分裂、僵局和顽固。</p><p>尽管如此，我确实认为莱昂哈特的文章抓住了有关美国治理现状的许多重要事实。美国的主要挑战已经从文化、身份和经济分配的内部斗争转向外部威胁，部分美国领导人和美国人民正在慢慢意识到这一事实。我也同意他的评估，即未来的两党倡议可能会包括更多的产业政策、更多与安全相关的政策以及帮助儿童的政策。</p><p>我还认为他错过了另一项重大政策——住房政策。高租金仍然在全国范围内引起广泛的不满，政府需要采取行动，以消除当地阻碍住房建设的障碍和限制。 There are some very encouraging signs that housing abundance could be a focus of bipartisan cooperation in the years to come — for example, <a href="https://www.semafor.com/article/05/23/2024/is-congress-having-its-yimby-moment">the YIMBY Act</a> that <a href="https://www.housingfinance.com/policy-legislation/yimby-act-passes-house_o">just passed</a> the House of Representatives.</p><h4> 3. 假科学似乎正在兴起</h4><p>每个人都知道科学中的复制危机；现在是应对欺诈危机的时候了。</p><p>最近我看到了一些关于伪造研究结果的非常令人不安的故事。著名的<a href="https://www.npr.org/2023/07/27/1190568472/dan-ariely-francesca-gino-harvard-dishonesty-fabricated-data">诚实研究人员</a>伪造数据、阿尔茨海默氏症<a href="https://www.npr.org/2023/07/19/1188828810/stanford-university-president-resigns">神经科学造假丑闻</a>迫使斯坦福大学校长下台，以及<a href="https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/nature-retracts-controversial-room-temperature-superconductor-study/">室温超导</a>研究也被造假。但这些似乎只是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/science/data-colada-debunk-stanford-president-research-14664f3">冰山一角</a>：</p><blockquote><p>每年的撤回数量大约占当年发表论文的十分之一，换句话说，就是千分之一。然而，这一数字较 2000 年约 40 篇撤稿大幅增长，远远超过了每年发表论文数量的增长速度。</p><p>近年来，撤稿数量急剧增加，主要原因有两个：首先，调查主要是由志愿者<a href="https://retractionwatch.com/2018/06/17/meet-the-scientific-sleuths-ten-whove-had-an-impact-on-the-scientific-literature/">梳理</a>学术文献中的异常情况进行的，其次是主要出版商（迟来的）认识到他们的<a href="https://retractionwatch.com/2023/03/09/wiley-paused-hindawi-special-issues-amid-quality-problems-lost-9-million-in-revenue/">商业模式</a>使他们容易受到<a href="https://retractionwatch.com/2021/12/20/revealed-the-inner-workings-of-a-paper-mill/">造纸厂</a>的影响——科学砍伐商店出售从作者身份到整个手稿的所有东西，以及需要发表以免灭亡的研究人员。</p></blockquote><p>现在有证据表明<a href="https://www.science.org/content/article/hundreds-cancer-papers-mention-cell-lines-don-t-seem-exist?utm_medium=ownedSocial&amp;utm_source=Twitter&amp;utm_campaign=NewsfromScience">大量癌症研究</a>都是伪造的：</p><blockquote><p>研究诚信侦探可能已经发现了识别欺诈论文的新危险信号，至少在癌症研究中是这样：关于显然不存在的人类细胞系的发现。这是最近一项研究得出的结论，该研究调查了 8 种细胞系，这些细胞系在 2004 年至 2023 年发表的 420 篇论文中始终存在拼写错误，其中包括癌症研究领域排名靠前的期刊。侦探们说，其中一些拼写错误可能是无意的错误，但 235 篇论文的子集提供了八行中七行的详细信息，<a href="https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/pdf/10.1002/ijc.34995">表明所报告的实验实际上并未进行</a>……而这些论文可能只是冰山一角， [作者詹妮弗]伯恩说。自2023年1月以来，已发表超过50,000篇有关人类癌细胞系的学术文章。 Byrne 的团队总共发现了 23 行拼写错误的行，但将其分析限制在 420 篇论文中提到的 8 行，以保持工作量可控。</p></blockquote><p>大量伪造的生物医学研究的发现现在实际上已经<a href="https://www.abc.net.au/news/2024-05-21/wiley-hindawi-articles-scandal-broader-crisis-trust-universities/103868662">停止了一些学术期刊的出版</a>：</p><blockquote><p>去年，Wiley 发生了一件奇怪的事情……其声明指出，由约 250 种期刊组成的 Hindawi 计划“由于某些特刊中存在受损文章而被暂时中止”……其中许多可疑论文声称是严重的医学研究……到 11 月，Wiley 已撤回多达 8,000 篇论文， <a href="https://www.science.org/content/article/paper-mills-bribing-editors-scholarly-journals-science-investigation-finds">告诉《科学》</a>杂志，它“在我们的投资组合中发现了数百名不良行为者”……一个月后，该公司以精致的企业<a href="https://s27.q4cdn.com/812717746/files/doc_financials/2024/q2/Q224-Earnings-Presentation-Final.pdf">语言宣布</a>：“Wiley 将取消 Hindawi 品牌”。</p></blockquote><p>科学作为一个企业，依赖于信任；科学家既没有时间也没有办法检查他们引用和建立的每一位研究人员的每一个结果。当大量研究人员公然进行欺诈时，整个系统就处于危险之中，因为在某些时候没有人可以相信其他人的结果。如果你担心巨人是虚幻的，那你就不能站在巨人的肩膀上。</p><p>然而，现代科学的激励措施似乎几乎是为了鼓励广泛的欺诈行为而设计的。科学成功的关键指标是 1) 在同行评审期刊上发表的论文，以及 2) 这些出版物的引用。正如<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goodhart%27s_law">古德哈特定律告诉我们的</a>那样，所有指标最终都会被利用。玩弄“发布或灭亡”系统的方法有很多——p-hacking、规范搜索、<a href="https://www.nber.org/papers/w32468">引用环</a>等。欺诈可能不是其中最简单或最安全的。但这几乎肯定是最具破坏性的。</p><p>同行评审对于防止欺诈的作用很差； even careful, diligent reviewers who might spot bad statistics or weak inferences will struggle to identify outright fakery.这就使得文化——一种对科学体系完整性的普遍自豪感——成为防范欺诈的前线。随着越来越多的资金投入科学领域，我们无法保证这种文化会完好无损。</p><p>这表明，为了维持科学事业，需要更多的“欺诈警察”来抓捕不法分子。但它也应该提出一个问题：研究人员是否应该因大量发表而获得奖励。奖励质量而不是数量可能会更好。</p><h4> 4. 欲望矫正的悄然兴起</h4><p>终极技术是什么？在许多经典科幻故事中，<em>超光速旅行</em>将使我们能够探索甚至殖民无限的新世界。在其他方面，它是<em>个性上传</em>，这将使我们能够创建数字世界来满足我们的任何和所有愿望。在另一些情况下，它是<em>通用人工智能</em>，它足够聪明，可以为我们提供我们想要的任何东西。</p><p>但有几个故事提出了一个更奇怪的想法，它可能胜过上述所有内容：<em>欲望改变</em>，这将使我们能够改变我们的基本心理。当我们可以改变自己以更好地适应我们已有的世界时，探索或创造新世界还有什么意义呢？</p><p>几千年来，人类一直在尝试通过冥想等方式改变我们的欲望。最近，我们在药物组合中添加了药物——抗抑郁药、抗焦虑药等。我们甚至尝试了<a href="https://www.amazon.com/Pleasure-Shock-Stimulation-Forgotten-Inventor/dp/1101986530">深部脑刺激</a>，以缓解严重的抑郁症。</p><p> Now we&#39;re discovering drugs that modify our desires in new and ever-more-interesting ways.研究人员发现，像 Ozempic 这样的 GLP-1 药物可以抑制食欲并实现减肥，实际上可以通过<a href="https://newatlas.com/medical/novo-nordisk-ozempic-weight-loss/">多种有趣的方式</a>改变人类的欲望：</p><blockquote><p>据丹麦研究人员称，目前突破性的减肥药物只是一个开始，他们正在努力开发一种针对大脑自然可塑性的新疗法，这种疗法可以抵消不良副作用并提供更长期的益处……</p><p>当前的 GLP-1 药物模仿进食后的自然荷尔蒙反应，发出“饱腹感”并减缓胃排空，而新疗法则使用 GLP-1 肽“走私”分子穿过血脑屏障并进入食欲。控制中心……他的新方法可以利用大脑的可塑性来巩固其食欲中心的新通路——这些通路在治疗停止后很长时间内仍将保留。</p></blockquote><p>还有迹象表明，这些药物有助于消除<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/search/research-news/19361/">对酒精和其他成瘾药物的渴望</a>。想象一下，如果成瘾者只需服用药物就能康复！</p><p>与此同时，毒品只是改变欲望的开始。 If pharmaceuticals are a blunt instrument, <a href="https://www.neuromodulation.com/about-neuromodulation">neuromodulation</a> — directly interfering with the brain&#39;s electrical circuits — has the potential to be a delicate scalpel. Neuralink, the most famous new brain implant device, is already <a href="https://www.wired.com/story/neuralink-first-patient-interview-noland-arbaugh-elon-musk/">achieving interesting results</a> , and it&#39;s only one of a number of devices and approaches currently being tested.</p><p> Perhaps the ultimate technological achievement will be to hack human nature itself.</p><h4> 5. People are thinking constructively about deregulation</h4><p> Deregulation, I always say, is too important to leave to the deregulators.</p><p> Well OK, I don&#39;t really always say that, but I plan to start now. Basically, for decades we Americans had a bunch of laissez-faire types — neoliberals, free marketers, libertarians, whatever you want to call them — tell us that the only good regulation was a repealed regulation. What each regulation <em>did</em> , exactly, was of secondary interest — deregulators would measure regulation by the number of pages in the federal register, or other such bulk measures.</p><p> That approach wasn&#39;t very helpful policy-wise, because essentially no politician wants to indiscriminately shrink the federal register. And when researchers started <a href="https://marginalrevolution.com/marginalrevolution/2018/02/federal-regulation-not-cause-declining-dynamism.html">looking into the idea</a> , they found that sheer volume of regulation was a very poor predictor of microeconomic outcomes.</p><p> So does that mean regulation is benign and we should leave it alone?恰恰相反。 It just means that “regulation” is an umbrella term that encompasses something far too general a category of policy to be simply good or simply bad. Instead, we need to dig into the specifics of regulations, in order to find out which ones help and which ones harm.</p><p> Fortunately, I see a lot of smart people doing exactly that these days. For example, <a href="https://www.niskanencenter.org/addressing-medicare-spending-and-hospital-consolidation-with-site-neutral-payments/">here&#39;s a Niskanen Center report</a> on site-based billing for Medicare, arguing that this causes the government to overpay for health care services and exacerbates monopoly power in the health care space, while not improving health outcomes for patients.</p><p> A second example is Alexander Kaufman&#39;s <a href="https://www.volts.wtf/p/the-obscure-but-extremely-important">crusade to improve building codes</a> . Rules about how buildings are built can have a huge impact on energy efficiency, but US building codes are highly fragmented and out of date.</p><p> A third example is <a href="https://www.commerce.gov/sites/default/files/streamlining_permitting_and_reducing_regulatory_burdens_for_domestic_manufacturing.pdf">this Commerce Department report</a> about how to improve permitting and other regulatory burdens for manufacturing. This is obviously very important if the US is going to revive its industrial base. Commerce asked a ton of manufacturers and manufacturing-related companies to tell them what the most burdensome regulations were. They identified about twenty sets of rules that are the most burdensome; most of these were environmental rules, and many related to permitting. The next task is to review these rules and ask how to protect the environment while still being able to build lots of factories quickly and cheaply.</p><p> An <a href="https://americanaffairsjournal.org/2023/11/its-not-just-nepa-reforming-environmental-permitting/">article by Thomas Hochman</a> in American Affairs supports this general idea, arguing that the Clean Air Act was written hastily and sloppily, and that a smart rewrite of the act would be able to protect air quality just as much while not blocking factories, power plants, or housing.</p><p> These are great efforts, and they are only a taste of what&#39;s going on out there. There&#39;s really a renaissance in thinking about how to improve regulation in the US — not to slash it, but to reduce it where necessary, rationalize it where appropriate, and even add new regulations if need be. This is a really exciting area of intellectual ferment and a vast opportunity for wonkish policy analysis. It could also be crucial to the future of our nation. </p><div><hr></div><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?"><span>现在订阅</span></a></p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/at-least-five-interesting-things-f84?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"> <a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/at-least-five-interesting-things-f84?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share"><span>分享</span></a></p><p></p><p></p>; 
A pivotal moment for Japan's national defenseA guest post by Jonathan Grady https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/a-pivotal-moment-for-japans-national https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/a-pivotal-moment-for-japans-nationalNoah Smith Sun, 26 May 2024 02:47:34 GMT <div class="captioned-image-container"><figure> <a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1c6f1065-ddc9-40ed-be2f-9af4c706ba6d_1090x727.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1c6f1065-ddc9-40ed-be2f-9af4c706ba6d_1090x727.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1c6f1065-ddc9-40ed-be2f-9af4c706ba6d_1090x727.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1c6f1065-ddc9-40ed-be2f-9af4c706ba6d_1090x727.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1c6f1065-ddc9-40ed-be2f-9af4c706ba6d_1090x727.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1c6f1065-ddc9-40ed-be2f-9af4c706ba6d_1090x727.jpeg" width="1090" height="727" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1c6f1065-ddc9-40ed-be2f-9af4c706ba6d_1090x727.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:727,&quot;width&quot;:1090,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:51965,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1c6f1065-ddc9-40ed-be2f-9af4c706ba6d_1090x727.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1c6f1065-ddc9-40ed-be2f-9af4c706ba6d_1090x727.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1c6f1065-ddc9-40ed-be2f-9af4c706ba6d_1090x727.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1c6f1065-ddc9-40ed-be2f-9af4c706ba6d_1090x727.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture></div></a> <polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line><figcaption class="image-caption"> Source: <a href="https://www.defense.gov/Multimedia/Photos/igphoto/2002963956/">USMC</a></figcaption></figure></div><p> <em>I&#39;ve been writing a lot about <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/americans-are-still-not-worried-enough">the threat of a major war in Asia</a> , but I haven&#39;t written much about Japan&#39;s role in that equation. And yet Japan would be at the very center of such a war. A Chinese seizure of Taiwan would <a href="https://thediplomat.com/2024/05/yes-japan-will-defend-taiwan/">put Japan&#39;s security in grave danger</a> . Here&#39;s a translated quote from a Chinese PLA officer <a href="https://globaltaiwan.org/2020/12/fortnightly-review-v-5-issue-24/">training manual</a> :</em></p><blockquote><p> <em>As soon as Taiwan is reunified with Mainland China, Japan&#39;s maritime lines of communication will fall completely within the striking ranges of China&#39;s fighters and bombers…Japan&#39;s economic activity and war-making potential will be basically destroyed…blockades can cause sea shipments to decrease and can even create a famine within the Japanese islands.</em></p></blockquote><p> <em>And China&#39;s ambassador to Japan <a href="https://x.com/Joel_P_Atkinson/status/1793424845356839304">recently said</a> that “once the country of Japan is tied to the tanks plotting to split China, the Japanese people will be brought into the fire.”</em></p><p> <em>Given the extreme imminent danger, Japan&#39;s defense policy going forward seems extremely important. I suggested that the country should <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/japan-and-south-korea-need-nuclear">deploy nuclear weapons</a> , but there are probably plenty of other things the country&#39;s leaders can do with regards to their conventional military capabilities.</em></p><p> <em>One person with plenty of ideas is <a href="https://x.com/_JonathanGrady">Jonathan Grady</a> , a founding principal at the consultancy <a href="https://www.canarygroupllc.com/">Canary Group</a> , who has done <a href="https://www.cnbc.com/quad-summit-and-china-game-theory-predictions-for-the-future-of-the-quad/">strategic analyses</a> of <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?app=desktop&amp;v=7sTDJzc76rU">the Quad&#39;s role</a> in Asian security and who sometimes writes about <a href="https://asia.nikkei.com/Opinion/To-pay-for-defense-buildup-Kishida-must-act-swiftly-on-taxes">Japanese defense policy</a> . In this guest post, he explains some of the economic and political hurdles Japan will have to overcome in order to continue its defense buildup and ensure its own security.</em></p><div><hr></div><h4> Japan Must Soon Decide on Major Defense Buildup</h4><p> Japan stands at a pivotal moment, facing urgent decisions about its defense strategy. Positioned to significantly enhance its defense capabilities, Japan is increasing its defense budget by 60% to assert more influence in Indo-Pacific security. This surge in spending is designed to bolster Tokyo&#39;s deterrence against China and promote regional peace. However, the ambitious plans are jeopardized by leader indecision, a complex political landscape and severe financial constraints that threaten to derail the historic buildup. With the stakes high – shaping deterrence planning across capitals while colliding against political survival – the decision outcome is significant. As Japan faces an election year, the lack of political resolve and clear funding mechanisms compels sincere action to determine the future scope and financing of its defense ambitions. These choices will define whether Japan realizes its full defense potential or faces significant compromises.</p><h4> <strong>Strengthening Japan&#39;s defense posture</strong></h4><p> The historic post-World War II buildup aims to enhance Tokyo&#39;s deterrence against Chinese aggression in the Indo-Pacific, a region crucial for global security. Additionally, it forms part of a broader international strategy to maintain a peaceful status quo amid competing territorial claims from China. Japan&#39;s unique island geography and the vulnerability of American bases on its soil underscore the urgency of these plans. Notably, Japan has the <a href="https://nationalinterest.org/blog/buzz/japan-now-has-mini-aircraft-carriers-carrying-f-35-fighters-209792">world&#39;s second largest fleet</a> of advanced F-35 fighter aircraft and is buying <a href="https://apnews.com/article/japan-us-tomahawk-missile-defense-0bcabfc4a87bf1a16beceec1b0c426fb">hundreds of Tomahawk cruise missiles</a> , enabling Tokyo counterstrike capabilities against enemy bases, and bolstering its defense and the security of American bases and troops. </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7a3f44e8-a898-4411-872d-2280905e99d0_781x521.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7a3f44e8-a898-4411-872d-2280905e99d0_781x521.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7a3f44e8-a898-4411-872d-2280905e99d0_781x521.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7a3f44e8-a898-4411-872d-2280905e99d0_781x521.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7a3f44e8-a898-4411-872d-2280905e99d0_781x521.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7a3f44e8-a898-4411-872d-2280905e99d0_781x521.jpeg" width="781" height="521" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/7a3f44e8-a898-4411-872d-2280905e99d0_781x521.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot